<h2 id="baba-is-you">Baba Is You</h2>

<p><img src="/assets/img/2019/babaisyou.png" alt="BABA is WIN" /></p>

<p>I got as close as I possibly could to 100% completing this game. I‚Äôve missed one flower somewhere and I have absolutely no willpower left to go and find it. And I think it‚Äôs safe to say I have mixed feelings, when all is said and done, about Baba Is You. When it‚Äôs firing on all cylinders, it‚Äôs a <em>fantastic</em> puzzle game - the premise itself is inventive, pushing blocks around to change the fundamental way those blocks interact and behave, and on the best levels Baba rewards playfulness and inventiveness. Those were the ones I absolutely loved, the ones where some interaction I didn‚Äôt see coming delighted me, where I accidentally changed myself into WIN, where moving walls around (because now I‚Äôm the wall) let me push something <em>just so,</em> the creative ones. This includes the moments where you manage to create alternative exits from puzzles, consuming actual spots on the map as the usual puzzle-solving reward - flowers - and breaking the boundaries of the game in a game that already breaks boundaries.</p>

<p>The problem is that those levels are not the majority.</p>

<p>Especially in the back half of the game, and <em>especially</em> if you want to see every flower and puzzle Baba Is You has to offer, you will almost <em>need</em> a walkthrough (and finding an up-to-date one can be hell, as puzzles have been updated evidently to eliminate solutions the developer didn‚Äôt approve of). So many of the puzzles past the halfway point of Baba are combinations of obtuse, seemingly arbitrary steps required to move things into the one square where they‚Äôll be effective, and doing so at exactly the right time, relying on you to understand not just the implications of what the words you‚Äôve strung together do, but also weird side effects, like what you can <em>get by</em> with by pushing it one square at a time by doing some weird sidestep.</p>

<p>This is why I have absolutely no intention of ever going back to this game. I consulted way too many walkthroughs and I got incredibly close and I‚Äôm done! I‚Äôm just done.</p>

<h2 id="the-longest-five-minutes">The Longest Five Minutes</h2>

<p><img src="/assets/img/2019/longest5min.jpg" alt="ugh" /></p>

<p>On the surface, this seems like it should be exactly my shit: facing the final boss of their quest, the appropriately-named hero Flash Back finds that he no longer recalls where he is, what he‚Äôs doing, or how he got there. The rest of his party is forced to remind him <em>because the Demon Lord‚Äôs still trying to kill them,</em> and the mechanic for doing so is a classic console RPG.</p>

<p>In reality, nothing you do in the RPG segments actually matters outside of the three objectives for each chapter. This ridiculous, already-thin plot wasn‚Äôt helped by the usual over the top NISA silliness (yeah, I get that it‚Äôs kind of a silly concept, but still) and it just put me off really quickly.</p>

<h2 id="the-surge">The Surge</h2>

<p><img src="/assets/img/2019/surge.png" alt="more ugh" /></p>

<p>It was free on PS Plus, and on the surface the concept was interesting - you play a wheelchair-bound character who gets strapped to a set of power armor that lets him regain his mobility, but the place he‚Äôs been shipped to, which honestly resembles nothing so much as a junkyard winding in and around warehouses, is full of rampaging robots. The combat system lets you aim your attacks at specific body parts, and once you‚Äôve chopped them off you might even be able to use them as weapons.</p>

<p>A great idea, but the combat itself feels really sloppy, especially the hit detection, and the environments are so one-note and bland. I expected nothing and I got what I expected. Finished! Next!</p>

<h2 id="fire-emblem-three-houses">Fire Emblem: Three Houses</h2>

<p><img src="/assets/img/2019/fe3h.jpg" alt="now this is more like it" /></p>

<p>Now, granted, I haven‚Äôt even picked up any of the DLC (not even the early free DLC, adding Jeritza and Anna as playable characters), but I played the heck out of Fire Emblem: Three Houses. It consumed me for close to two or three months. I loved it, to be blunt. I loved the inclusion of the time-reversal mechanic as a compromise between casual and hardcore mode, and thus for the first time since the GBA games I played a Fire Emblem on hardcore all the way to the end. I didn‚Äôt even lose anyone, no matter how much I wanted to recruit Lorenz and ‚Äúaccidentally‚Äù send him to his death. Oops. Such a shame.</p>

<p>I want to go back and replay one of the other routes - possibly the Blue Lions, since I‚Äôve heard they‚Äôre the most completely different from the other routes - but I haven‚Äôt found the energy to pick it back up and be ready to devote myself to what is actually the longest route in the game. I‚Äôve also heard the new ‚Äúsewer kids‚Äù DLC is hard in really cheap, bad ways, and that doesn‚Äôt exactly encourage me to jump back in, either. But I really enjoyed the route I did play, which I felt struck a good balance between getting a picture of the overall plot, and also length of actual play.</p>

<p>(And in case you‚Äôre extremely curious, I chose the Church route in the end and married Rhea.)</p>

